But essentially, our post processing is going to control a host of different artistic or visual effects into our scene.

56
00:04:38.000 --> 00:04:42.000
And we will see that later exemplified when we actually have some of our lighting.

57
00:04:42.000 --> 00:04:44.000
But for now, we can just follow along with this.

58
00:04:44.000 --> 00:04:49.000
So the first thing that I want to do is with my post processing volume selected,

59
00:04:49.000 --> 00:04:50.000
go over into my details panel.

60
00:04:50.000 --> 00:04:56.000
I'm going to scroll all the way down until I see the post processing volume settings.

61
00:04:56.000 --> 00:05:00.000
And the first thing that I want to do is check the infinite extent unbound.

62
00:05:00.000 --> 00:05:08.000
Now, there are situations where you may want to localize or control your post processing effects within just that volume or that shape.

63
00:05:08.000 --> 00:05:12.000
And that is the default nature and behavior of our post processing volumes.

64
00:05:12.000 --> 00:05:19.000
However, for this, we don't want it to we don't want those effects to be contained just to the post processing volume shape.

65
00:05:19.000 --> 00:05:25.000
We want them to continue to propagate no matter where the camera is positioned.

66
00:05:25.000 --> 00:05:29.000
And that's what infinite extent unbound is going to do.

67
00:05:29.000 --> 00:05:33.000
All right. So with that checked and we have enabled, we're going to scroll back up.

68
00:05:33.000 --> 00:05:36.000
And the first thing I'm going to look for is my exposure tab.

69
00:05:37.000 --> 00:05:43.000
So if I expand this out, anytime that we have a setting and we check the box,

70
00:05:43.000 --> 00:05:49.000
we are now overriding whatever the default behavior or the current setting is based off a priority,

71
00:05:49.000 --> 00:05:55.000
which in this case, as we only have one post processing volume, we are simply just going to change this setting.

72
00:05:55.000 --> 00:05:59.000
So on our exposure compensation, I'm going to change this to negative five point five.

73
00:05:59.000 --> 00:06:01.000
What does that number come from?

74
00:06:01.000 --> 00:06:07.000
Simply just because of the light values that we're using, the fact that we're trying to adhere to more realistic values.

75
00:06:07.000 --> 00:06:09.000
We'll find this later with our directional light.

76
00:06:09.000 --> 00:06:15.000
A value of negative five point five is going to give us correct or at least visually correct exposure in our scene.

77
00:06:15.000 --> 00:06:21.000
However, note that this particular parameter you can adjust up or down if your scene is too bright or too dark.

78
00:06:21.000 --> 00:06:23.000
That's not the most critical component.

79
00:06:23.000 --> 00:06:28.000
The next component that we actually want to change is our min and max.

80
00:06:28.000 --> 00:06:32.000
In fact, this is going to be directly correlated with our exposure compensation.

81
00:06:32.000 --> 00:06:41.000
So if we clamp these both at one and one or zero and zero or whatever the same value is, this essentially fix the auto exposure.

82
00:06:41.000 --> 00:06:49.000
So now the engine won't try to adjust the exposure of our in-game camera or how we're viewing based off of these numbers.

83
00:06:50.000 --> 00:07:00.000
So those few settings right there should be all that we need to disable our auto exposure and allow the post processing volume take effect across the whole scene.

84
00:07:00.000 --> 00:07:06.000
Now, we could go in as well, as you had heard me mention, too, about adjusting some of our artistic effects.

85
00:07:06.000 --> 00:07:12.000
For example, I could take chromatic aberration, check the intensity to make sure it does, in fact, overwrite at zero.

86
00:07:12.000 --> 00:07:16.000
We could change our bloom intensity to zero as well.

87
00:07:16.000 --> 00:07:20.000
So again, anything artistic related, disabling it.

88
00:07:20.000 --> 00:07:24.000
Of course, we can always re-enable these later through a secondary post processing volume,

89
00:07:24.000 --> 00:07:30.000
but simply just check the parameter itself and go ahead and set the value to zero.
